React Server Components: Complete Guide 2024

React Server Components (RSC) revolutionize how we build React applications by enabling server-side rendering of specific components.

What are Server Components?

Server Components are React components that run exclusively on the server. They offer major advantages: reduced JavaScript bundle (code isn't sent to the client), direct data access with direct connection to databases, and enhanced security as API keys stay server-side.

Server vs Client Components

Server Components:
```javascript
// app/posts/page.js (Server Component by default)
import { getPosts } from '@/lib/database'

export default async function PostsPage() {
  const posts = await getPosts()
  return (
    <div>
      {posts.map(post => (
        <article key={post.id}>
          <h2>{post.title}</h2>
          <p>{post.excerpt}</p>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  )
}
```

Client Components:
```javascript
'use client'
import { useState } from 'react'

export default function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0)
  return (
    <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>
      Counter: {count}
    </button>
  )
}
```

Best Practices

Use Server Components by default unless interactivity is needed. Minimize Client Components to reduce client-side JavaScript. Use smart composition to efficiently combine both types.

Practical Use Cases

```javascript
// Server Component for data
async function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const user = await fetchUser(userId)
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{user.name}</h1>
      <UserActions user={user} /> {/* Client Component */}
    </div>
  )
}
```

Performance Optimization

Server Components enable reduced Time to Interactive (TTI), improved First Contentful Paint (FCP), decreased JavaScript bundle size, and better SEO naturally.

Architecture Benefits

Zero client-side JavaScript for static content, automatic code splitting at component level, streaming support for progressive loading, and better caching strategies with server-side rendering.

React Server Components represent the future of React development. By mastering this technology, you'll create faster, more secure, and more maintainable applications.

TypeScript: Best Practices for 2024

TypeScript continues to evolve and establish itself as the standard for modern JavaScript development. Here are the essential best practices for 2024.

Strict Configuration

Optimal tsconfig.json:
```json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "strict": true,
    "noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true,
    "exactOptionalPropertyTypes": true,
    "noImplicitReturns": true,
    "noFallthroughCasesInSwitch": true
  }
}
```

Advanced Utility Types

Conditional Types:
```typescript
type ApiResponse<T> = T extends string 
  ? { message: T } 
  : { data: T }

type StringResponse = ApiResponse<string> // { message: string }
type DataResponse = ApiResponse<User[]>   // { data: User[] }
```

Mapped Types:
```typescript
type Partial<T> = {
  [P in keyof T]?: T[P]
}
```

Modern Patterns

Branded Types:
```typescript
type UserId = string & { __brand: 'UserId' }
type Email = string & { __brand: 'Email' }

function createUser(id: UserId, email: Email) {
  // Type safety guaranteed
}
```

Discriminated Unions:
```typescript
type LoadingState = 
  | { status: 'loading' }
  | { status: 'success'; data: any }
  | { status: 'error'; error: string }

function handleState(state: LoadingState) {
  switch (state.status) {
    case 'loading': return 'Loading...'
    case 'success': return state.data
    case 'error': return state.error
  }
}
```

Validation with Zod

```typescript
import { z } from 'zod'

const UserSchema = z.object({
  id: z.string().uuid(),
  email: z.string().email(),
  age: z.number().min(0).max(120)
})

type User = z.infer<typeof UserSchema>
```

Efficient Type Guards

```typescript
function isString(value: unknown): value is string {
  return typeof value === 'string'
}

function processValue(value: unknown) {
  if (isString(value)) {
    return value.toUpperCase()
  }
}
```

Development Tips

Use strict mode for better type safety. Leverage utility types for code reusability. Implement proper error handling with Result types. Use const assertions for better type inference.

These TypeScript best practices will help you create more robust, maintainable, and performant applications. Investment in strict configuration translates to fewer bugs and better developer experience.
